%description:
Round-trip serialization test for the packet serializers.

Reads each record of a pcap file, deserializes it into its most specific typed
chunks using the generic PacketDissector, re-serializes the result, and compares
it byte-by-byte with the original frame. The generic dissector automatically
covers every registered protocol; unknown payloads fall back to raw bytes and
round-trip trivially. This replaces the former hand-written, per-protocol
deserialization chain.

The engine lives in tests/unit/lib/SerializerTestLib.{h,cc}.

It also reports serializer coverage: the exercised (USED ...) and never-invoked
(UNTESTED ...) registered serializers, plus a raw-bytes summary. The full lists
are printed for humans to drive corpus expansion; only a small baseline of core
serializers is gated below (so a silent coverage loss is caught), together with
the requirement that no whole packet fall back to raw bytes (TOPLEVEL-RAWBYTES).

NOTE: this test currently FAILS on purpose. Beyond the always-green baseline
pcaps, it also runs real captures from the Wireshark wiki (pcap/wireshark/,
fetched by fetch_wireshark_captures.sh) whose expected result is a clean
round-trip -- but several surface genuine serializer bugs, so the test fails
until they are fixed. Known failures (each fix removes one):
  - ospf.cap        : "Cannot convert between integer units" (OSPF serializer)
  - IGMP-dataset.pcap: IGMP type 0xff not supported (round-trip of that type)
  - sctp-www.cap    : "simtime_t: Cannot represent ..." (large value into simtime)
  - mpls-basic.cap  : "Cannot find serializer for inet::RsvpMessage" (dissector without serializer)
  - ptpv2.pcap      : gPTP GptpSync/GptpMessageType unimplemented
The pim-reg.cap, v6-http.cap, vlan.cap and PPP-config.cap captures round-trip
cleanly today.

%includes:
#include "SerializerTestLib.h"

%global:

using namespace inet;

%activity:

beginSerializerCoverage();

testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/rarp_request.pcap", false);
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/rarp_req_reply.pcap", false);
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/Ethernet_Pause_Frame.pcap", false);
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/eth_fcs_good.pcap", true);
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/v6.pcap", false);

// captures downloaded from the Wireshark wiki (see fetch_wireshark_captures.sh)
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/wireshark/ospf.cap", false);
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/wireshark/IGMP-dataset.pcap", false);
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/wireshark/pim-reg.cap", false);
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/wireshark/sctp-www.cap", false);
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/wireshark/v6-http.cap", false);
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/wireshark/vlan.cap", false);
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/wireshark/mpls-basic.cap", false);
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/wireshark/PPP-config.cap", false);
testPcapSerialization("../../pcap/wireshark/ptpv2.pcap", false);

reportSerializerCoverage();

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/rarp_request.pcap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/rarp_req_reply.pcap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/Ethernet_Pause_Frame.pcap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/eth_fcs_good.pcap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/v6.pcap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/wireshark/ospf.cap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/wireshark/IGMP-dataset.pcap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/wireshark/pim-reg.cap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/wireshark/sctp-www.cap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/wireshark/v6-http.cap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/wireshark/vlan.cap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/wireshark/mpls-basic.cap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/wireshark/PPP-config.cap

%contains: stdout
All frames are the same in file ../../pcap/wireshark/ptpv2.pcap

%not-contains: stdout
differ

%not-contains: stdout
EXCEPTION

%contains: stdout
USED inet::EthernetMacHeader

%contains: stdout
USED inet::EthernetFcs

%contains: stdout
USED inet::ArpPacket

%contains: stdout
USED inet::Ipv4Header

%contains: stdout
USED inet::Ipv6Header

%contains: stdout
USED inet::IcmpHeader

%contains: stdout
USED inet::Icmpv6Header

%contains: stdout
USED inet::tcp::TcpHeader

%contains: stdout
USED inet::UdpHeader

%not-contains: stdout
TOPLEVEL-RAWBYTES
